<TD valign=top><FONT FACE="Trebuchet MS, Arial, Helvetica" COLOR="#333399"><b>Alrien</b></FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Trebuchet MS, Arial, Helvetica" SIZE="1" COLOR="#333399"><B>Newbie</B></font><BR><BR><FONT FACE="Trebuchet MS, Arial, Helvetica" SIZE="1" COLOR="#333399">Joined: Jul 30, 2001</FONT><br><FONT FACE="Trebuchet MS, Arial, Helvetica" SIZE="1" COLOR="#333399">Posts: 7</FONT></td><TD valign="top"><img src="/boards/images/posticon.gif"><FONT FACE="Trebuchet MS, Arial, Helvetica" SIZE="1" COLOR="#333399">Posted: 2001-08-03 02:01&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp<HR></font>

<FONT COLOR="#333399" face="Trebuchet MS, Arial, Helvetica">There is so much more to how a druid can contribute to a group, aside from having a large mana pool.<BR><BR>This can mean, freeing up some slots for ac/resist/hp gear, which would cause you to take less damage, which could lead to the cleric not having to heal you, which leads to less cleric aggro and more mana for the cleric.  There are so many possibilities.<BR><BR>And when the fist hits the shan - it's NOT having a large mana pool that saves you.  It's using you brain.<BR><BR>It's understanding which mob is being attacked, which mob the enchanter is trying to hold down and maybe helping out with a root park on a "free mob."<BR><BR>It's aggroing a mob off the cleric so he can heal the tank.<BR><BR>It's keeping aggro off youself and doing that evac.<BR><BR>I am NOT saying that mana is not important.  Obviously you need mana to do all this, but once you are around the 180 wis mark, the priority of improving your mana cap yields to things like ac/resists/hp gear.<BR><BR>A lot of casting isn't going to save you in a bad situation - it's your creativity and tactics that will.<BR><BR>Anyway, I'm not at all promoting the idea of "losing wis to look cool."  That is purely up to the player.<BR><BR>What I am saying is that the difference 10 wisdom makes near the 200 cap is very minor.  And - in fact - the slots which boost wis can be better spent boosting other stats.<BR><BR>My favorite comparison is between the platinum armband and azure sleeves.  Sure this is a more extreme case, but I cannot believe the number of druids that sacrafice 13 ac for 3 wis.<BR><BR>Look at it this way:<BR><BR>Lets say with 180 wis it takes you 1 minute to med from oom to "gtg status."<BR><BR>So, with 200 wis, it will STILL take only 1 minute to med from oom to "gtg status."<BR><BR>(You might have less blue, but it's the *same* amount of mana.)<BR><BR>The only difference is that with 200 wis you have more EMPTY mana.<BR><BR>Unless you're going in on a break and have the *luxury* of medding to FM, standard exp grinding groups will keep your mana bar down to around 60 most of the time.  You usually won't even be able to tap into the "extra 20 wis pool."<BR><BR>Make sense?<BR><BR>Alrien</FONT><BR></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR="#e6ebd7"><TD nowrap align="left">&nbsp;</TD><TD><table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%"><tr><td>&nbsp;&nbsp<a href="/boards/bb_profile.php?mode=view&user=1328"><img src="/boards/images/profile.gif" border=0 alt="View Profile of Alrien"></a>
