<TD valign=top><FONT FACE="Trebuchet MS, Arial, Helvetica" COLOR="#333399"><b>Quelm</b></FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Trebuchet MS, Arial, Helvetica" SIZE="1" COLOR="#333399"><B>Woods Person</B></font><BR><BR><FONT FACE="Trebuchet MS, Arial, Helvetica" SIZE="1" COLOR="#333399">Joined: Jun 13, 2001</FONT><br><FONT FACE="Trebuchet MS, Arial, Helvetica" SIZE="1" COLOR="#333399">Posts: 41</FONT></td><TD valign="top"><img src="/boards/images/posticon.gif"><FONT FACE="Trebuchet MS, Arial, Helvetica" SIZE="1" COLOR="#333399">Posted: 2001-08-03 12:02&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp<HR></font>

<FONT COLOR="#333399" face="Trebuchet MS, Arial, Helvetica"><b>In this sitution mana regen rate and any other Sh** isnt going to help you out, <BR>the bigger your mana pool is, the more heals you can get off, simple as that.</b><BR><BR>At level 51, the difference between 200 wis and 175 wis is *1* Superior Heal spell on<BR>a Full -> OOM mana-dump.  On a 60M->OOM dump, it isn't even a single heal.  In xp groups, I see single, maybe double pulls all night.  Repops, wanderers, breaking new areas and tough pulls can bring more, but for the most part, the situation is under control all night long.  Situations where all casters *must* dump all their mana are rare.  Situations where 3/4ths of a superior heal are going to save the day are even rarer.  Druids are not a "hero" class, their true contribution to a party comes over extended periods of time.<BR><BR>Anyway, I play at about 80 / 90 mana all evening.  When things are really close, I'll <BR>break my evac limit for an extra heal.  In my xp groups, I haven't often found mana pool<BR>size to be an issue.  When it is, I swap plat jaspers in for velium fire opal rings, drop my tattered mantle for a prayer shawl and switch an SBS out in favor of a CGS.  I have a wisdom set, I just don't use it much.  Last night for example, primary (only) healer, primary (only) evacer, snare duty, monk (60) tanking, no chanter, 5 person group in HS.  We picked up good xp and a few drops.  I stayed in AC gear all night, because I felt safer, and because I felt my party was safer with a tougher healer/evacer.  Did we evac?  No.  Did I get hit?  About 10 times in 3 hours.  The point is, if things got really ugly, I stood a<BR>better chance of: A) surviving if I was forced to choose between healing and picking up agro or letting a party member die, and B) living long enough to evac.  IMO, I was potentially *more* useful than a druid with lower ac and higher wisdom.<BR><BR>Raids are a different story, AC goes out the window there.<BR><BR>"I have yet to find an efficient puller who waits until everyone is FM before he pulls another."<BR>"...but if you are grouped with other casters you will have time to med to full or closer to it."<BR><BR>umm, make up your mind  <IMG SRC="/boards/images/smiles/icon_smile.gif">  Are you, or are you not FM before most fights?  IMO, it is all about regulating mana use over time, not bursts.<BR><BR>-Quelm, 54 Wanderer<BR>Drunken Tsunami, Terris-Thule<BR><BR><font size=-1>[ This Message was edited by: Quelm on 2001-08-03 12:02 ]</font></FONT><BR></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR="#e6ebd7"><TD nowrap align="left">&nbsp;</TD><TD><table border="1" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%"><tr><td>&nbsp;&nbsp<a href="/boards/bb_profile.php?mode=view&user=184"><img src="/boards/images/profile.gif" border=0 alt="View Profile of Quelm"></a>
